    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@holiman, started working on this but there's a little issue I'd like clarified.\r\n\r\n`clef addpw <address> <password>` is described as:\r\n> The addpw command stores a password for a given address (keyfile). If you invoke it with only one parameter, it will remove any stored credential for that address (keyfile)\r\n\r\nThat would translate to the following behaviors:\r\n\r\n```gherkin\r\nScenario: Add new credential\r\n  Given a user run's \"clef addpw 0x0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 abc\"\r\n  When checking the credentials file\r\n  Then \"0x0000000000000000000000000000000000000000\" exists as a key\r\n\r\nScenario: Remove credential\r\n  Given I run \"clef addpw 0x0000000000000000000000000000000000000000\"\r\n  When checking the credentials file\r\n  Then \"0x0000000000000000000000000000000000000000\" does not exist as a key\r\n```\r\n\r\n**The problem:**\r\n1. Dropping the `<password>` arg for the prompt to fulfill this issue's requirements would conflict with the described \"Remove credential\" behavior.\r\n2. \"Remove credential\" behavior is not yet implemented (or I just couldn't get it to work ðŸ˜…).\r\n\r\n**Proposed solution**\r\n1. `addpw` is single purpose, remove reference in the description about \"Remove credential\"\r\n2. ~~Add a new `removepw` command to handle \"Remove credential\"~~ perhaps better as a separate issue/pr?",
